text_answer.content: I chose "yes" on bias, because the analyzing information question is misleading as to what constitutes a "traditional classroom learning" environment, and that problem-solving and creativity, as the article attributes to positives about daydreaming, are excluded from the traditional classroom. The classroom provides a wide variety of learning opportunities that promote problem-solving and creativity, such as group projects, gallery walks, writing projects from stories to poems to plays, etc. The classroom is simply a synchronous environment where learning takes place moderated by a teacher. By creating a dissonance between classroom learning and daydreaming (and even what we do each day in our learning centers with our students!) is disparaging to teachers and the educational process.
